In this article, President Barack Obama proclaims April as National Child Abuse Prevention Month. He emphasizes the importance of protecting children, preventing child abuse, and promoting healthy families. The President acknowledges that child abuse, including sexual, emotional, and physical abuse, remains a threat to many children in the United States. He urges parents, guardians, relatives, neighbors, and the government to take responsibility in preventing these crimes. The Obama Administration is dedicated to supporting future generations by engaging parents in their children's development, ensuring the well-being of families, and creating opportunities for all Americans. The government is also collaborating with federal, state, and local agencies to improve early childhood services and enhance the lives of young children and their families. The President encourages all Americans to visit a website for more information on preventing child abuse in their communities.